ce:section.ce:para:
SEM analysis is performed to confirm the above observations (Fig. 5
                           ). For the PEDOT:PSS/Te film, as seen, Te nano-rods are separated from the surface of the polymeric matrix and distributed on its surface with a large density (Fig. 5a), this indicates to the weak interaction between the Te nano-rods and PEDOT:PSS which reflected in the weak compatibility between them. However, when 1 wt% of NC decorated the Te surface, a high degree of homogeneity and compatibility was observed for NC@Te nano-particles which were well dispersed in the PEDOT:PSS matrix. As seen, a small amount of NC@Te nanoparticles was separated and located on the polymer surface and the largest amount of Te nanoparticles sink and embedded into the polymer matrix (Fig. 5b). With increasing the amount of NC in the polymeric matrix, a better dispersion of NC@Te nano-particles in the polymer matrix was obtained thanks to the strong π-π interfacial interaction between the NC on the surface of Te and the PEDOT:PSS polymer chains (Fig. 5c-e). When increasing the concentration of NC to reach 4 wt%, the SEM images show an excellent dispersion behavior of the NC@Te in the whole polymeric matrix with a high adhesion property among the NC@Te and the polymeric matrix due to the increase in the NC in the polymeric matrix which leads to increasing the strong π-π interfacial interactions inside the matrix and obtaining a high degree of compatibility, homogeneity, adhesion and well-dispersion inside the polymeric matrix (Fig. 5e). Also, SEM images show that a high packing density structure with increasing the NC concentration to 4 wt%. Also, Fig. 5f shows the cross section image of 4 wt% sample, which proves the good embedding of NC@Te nano-particles inside the polymeric matrix with high packing density. As seen, the good dispersion of NC@Te nano-particles inside the polymeric matrix allows the nitrogen/static air gaseous atmosphere to fill and occupy all the voids and pores inside the matrix and drive the system to saturation, and this illustrates why the k
                           ⊥ values slightly varied after 1 wt% of NC (approximately fixed after 1 wt% of NC). In fact this structure leads to improving the connectivity behavior (especially, the particle-to-particle connective behavior), improving the aspect ratio factor, and increasing σ. As reported earlier [1,3,4,34-41,70,71] these structures/morphologies have great benefits in increasing the carrier mobility, increasing the conductivity and hence improving the thermoelectric functions. Moreover this morphology has a great merit in increasing the phonon scattering at the boundary interfaces during the process of heat transfer. This leads to reducing the mean free path of phonons just when embedding the nano-fillers in the polymeric matrix and hence reducing the value of k.

The figure of merit zT⊥ and zT// were evaluated at room temperature and plotted with the NC content (Fig. 12
                           ). As shown, zT⊥ and zT// values increased with increasing the NC content inside the films. However, zT⊥ is higher than zT// due to the k
                           ⊥ is lower than k
                           //. In fact, the increase in zT values is ascribed to the increase in PF with increasing the NC content. zT⊥ shows an optimum value at 3 wt% of NC due to the optimized PF at the same content.
